continuous-integration.md
     1Рєњ# Running `mdbook` in continuous integration
     3РєњThere are a variety of services such as [GitHub Actions] or [GitLab CI/CD] which can be used to test and deploy your book automatically.
     4Рєњ
     5РєњThe following provides some general guidelines on how to configure your service to run mdBook.
     6РєњSpecific recipes can be found at the [Automated Deployment] wiki page.
     7Рєњ
     8Рєњ[GitHub Actions]: https://docs.github.com/en/actions
     9Рєњ[GitLab CI/CD]: https://docs.gitlab.com/ee/ci/
    10Рєњ[Automated Deployment]: https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/wiki/Automated-Deployment
    11Рєњ
    12Рєњ## Installing mdBook
    14РєњThere are several different strategies for installing mdBook.
    15РєњThe particular method depends on your needs and preferences.
    16Рєњ
    17Рєњ### Pre-compiled binaries
    19РєњPerhaps the easiest method is to use the pre-compiled binaries found on the [GitHub Releases page][releases].
    20РєњA simple approach would be to use the popular `curl` CLI tool to download the executable:
    21Рєњ
      РєњРђд
    39Рєњ### Building from source
    41РєњBuilding from source will require having Rust installed.
    42РєњSome services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    43Рєњ
      РєњРђд
    67Рєњ## Running tests
    69РєњYou may want to run tests using [`mdbook test`] every time you push a change or create a pull request.
    70РєњThis can be used to validate Rust code examples in the book.
    71Рєњ
    72РєњThis will require having Rust installed.
    73РєњSome services have Rust pre-installed, but if your service does not, you will need to add a step to install it.
    74Рєњ
      РєњРђд
    83Рєњ## Deploying
    85РєњYou may want to automatically deploy your book.
    86РєњSome may want to do this every time a change is pushed, and others may want to only deploy when a specific release is tagged.
    87Рєњ
    88РєњYou'll also need to understand the specifics on how to push a change to your web service.
    89РєњFor example, [GitHub Pages] just requires committing the output onto a specific git branch.
    90РєњOther services may require using something like SSH to connect to a remote server.
      РєњРђд
   100Рєњ### 404 handling
   102РєњmdBook automatically generates a 404 page to be used for broken links.
   103РєњThe default output is a file named `404.html` at the root of the book.
   104РєњSome services like [GitHub Pages] will automatically use this page for broken links.
      РєњРђд

for_developers/README.md
     1Рєњ# For developers
     3РєњWhile `mdbook` is mainly used as a command line tool, you can also import the
     4Рєњunderlying libraries directly and use those to manage a book. It also has a fairly
     5Рєњflexible plugin mechanism, allowing you to create your own custom tooling and
     6Рєњconsumers (often referred to as *backends*) if you need to do some analysis of
     7Рєњthe book or render it in a different format.
     8Рєњ
     9РєњThe *For Developers* chapters are here to show you the more advanced usage of
    10Рєњ`mdbook`.
    11Рєњ
    12РєњThe two main ways a developer can hook into the book's build process is via,
    13Рєњ
    14Рєњ- [Preprocessors](preprocessors.md)
    15Рєњ- [Alternative Backends](backends.md)
    16Рєњ
    17Рєњ## The build process
    19РєњThe process of rendering a book project goes through several steps.
    20Рєњ
    21Рєњ1. Load the book
    22Рєњ    - Parse the `book.toml`, falling back to the default `Config` if it doesn't
    23Рєњ       exist
    24Рєњ    - Load the book chapters into memory
    25Рєњ    - Discover which preprocessors/backends should be used
    26Рєњ2. For each backend:
    27Рєњ   1. Run all the preprocessors.
    28Рєњ   2. Call the backend to render the processed result.
    29Рєњ
    30Рєњ## Using `mdbook` as a library
    32РєњThe `mdbook` binary is just a wrapper around the underlying mdBook crates,
    33Рєњexposing their functionality as a command-line program. If you want to
    34Рєњprogrammatically drive mdBook, you can use the [`mdbook-driver`] crate.
    35РєњThis can be used to add your own functionality or tweak the build process.
    36Рєњ
    37РєњThe easiest way to find out how to use the `mdbook-driver` crate is by looking at the
    38Рєњ[API Docs]. The top level documentation explains how one would use the
    39Рєњ[`MDBook`] type to load and build a book, while the [config] module gives a good
    40Рєњexplanation on the configuration system.
    41Рєњ
    42Рєњ[`MDBook`]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/struct.MDBook.html
    43Рєњ[API Docs]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/
    44Рєњ[config]: https://docs.rs/mdbook-driver/latest/mdbook_driver/config/index.html

for_developers/backends.md
     1Рєњ# Alternative backends
     3РєњA "backend" is simply a program which `mdbook` will invoke during the book
     4Рєњrendering process. This program is passed a JSON representation of the book and
     5Рєњconfiguration information via `stdin`. Once the backend receives this
     6Рєњinformation it is free to do whatever it wants.
     7Рєњ
     8РєњSee [Configuring Renderers](../format/configuration/renderers.md) for more information about using backends.
     9Рєњ
    10РєњThe community has developed several backends.
    11РєњSee the [Third Party Plugins] wiki page for a list of available backends.
    12Рєњ
    13Рєњ## Setting up Рђд
    53Рєњ## Inspecting the book Рђд
    82Рєњ## Enabling the backend Рђд
   159Рєњ## Configuration Рђд
   219Рєњ## Output and signalling failure Рђд
   322Рєњ## Wrapping up Рђд

